    ]},
    { category: "european", tests: [
      { input: "15.03.2024", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "{ year: 2024, month: 3, day: 15 }" },
      { input: "13/02/2024", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "{ year: 2024, month: 2, day: 13 } (auto-disambiguated)" }
    ]},
    { category: "natural-language", tests: [
      { input: "yesterday", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "{ year: 2026, month: 3, day: 10 }" },
      { input: "next Tuesday", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "{ year: 2026, month: 3, day: 17 }" },
      { input: "in 3 days", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "{ year: 2026, month: 3, day: 14 }" }
    ]},
    { category: "error", tests: [
      { input: "not-a-date-at-all", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "ValueError" },
      { input: "", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "ValueError" },
      { input: "   ", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "ValueError" }
    ]},
    { category: "boundary", tests: [
      { input: "02/29/2025", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "ValueError (non-leap year)" },
      { input: "02/29/2000", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "{ year: 2000, month: 2, day: 29 } (leap year)" }
    ]},
    { category: "ambiguous", tests: [
      { input: "01/02/2024", verdict: "? ambiguous", result: "US → Jan 2 OR European → Feb 1" },
      { input: "March 2024", verdict: "? ambiguous", result: "No day — default to 1st or error?" },
      { input: "12/11/2024", verdict: "? ambiguous", result: "US → Dec 11 OR European → Nov 12" }
    ]},
    { category: "mixed-format", tests: [
      { input: "March 15, 2024 10:30:00Z", verdict: "✓ passing", result: "{ year: 2024, month: 3, day: 15 }" }
    ]}
  ]

  yield coverage-report ≡ "Coverage score: 8/10. 18 tests total: 7 initial happy-path tests (all passing), 11 edge tests (8 passing, 3 ambiguous). Coverage spans 8 categories: ISO 8601, US format, European format, natural language, error cases, calendar boundaries, ambiguous inputs, and mixed formats. Remaining gaps: negative relative dates ('in -1 days'), century-boundary leap year negatives (02/29/2100). Three spec ambiguities identified requiring author clarification."

  yield spec-questions ≡ [
    "Q1: When a date string matches both US and European formats with different results (e.g., '01/02/2024'), which format takes priority? Suggestion: add a locale parameter or document a default priority.",
    "Q2: Should partial dates (e.g., 'March 2024' with no day) raise ValueError or default the missing field? The spec says 'Returns a Date with year, month, day fields' — this implies all three are required.",
    "Q3: What timezone anchors relative date expressions ('yesterday', 'next Tuesday', 'in 3 days')? Is it UTC, the system timezone, or a configurable parameter?"
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ complete-suite covers initial tests + all edge tests → ✓ (7 + 11 = 18 tests across 8 categories)
--   ⊨ coverage-report references the coverage-score → ✓ ("Coverage score: 8/10")
--   ⊨ if len(spec-questions) > 0 then at least one ambiguity was found → ✓ (3 questions, 3 ambiguities)
--   ⊨ complete-suite is organized by category → ✓ (8 category groups)

-- needs-more-work: SKIPPED (guard false). Yields:
--   complete-suite ≡ ⊥
--   coverage-report ≡ ⊥
--   spec-questions ≡ ⊥

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- QUIESCENCE
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- All cells frozen or skipped. No cell in the ready set. Program complete.
--
-- Frozen cells (23 eval-one steps total across iterations):
--   Pre-loop: function-spec, generate-initial-tests, run-tests
--   ⊢∘ iter 0: discover-edge-cases, spawn-edge-tests,
--     edge-test-0..5 (6 cells), assess-coverage, refine-test-suite
--   ⊢∘ iter 1: discover-edge-cases, spawn-edge-tests,
--     edge-test-6..10 (5 cells), assess-coverage (with retry), refine-test-suite
--   Post-loop: final-report
--
-- Skipped cells (1):
--   needs-more-work (guard false → yields ⊥)
--
-- Spawned cells: 11 total (6 from iter 0, 5 from iter 1) via accumulate mode
-- ⊢∘ evolve used 2 of 3 allowed iterations.
-- Coverage: 8/10 with 18 tests and 3 spec clarifications.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢= obs-self-building-suite-works
  given §04-self-building-test-suite
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "THE TEST SUITE GENUINELY BUILT ITSELF: Starting from 7 happy-path tests, the program discovered 11 edge cases across 2 iterations without any human guidance. The key mechanism: edge-test cells yield deeper-edges[] — each test GENERATES suggestions for more tests. This is recursive discovery: testing reveals gaps, gaps spawn tests, tests reveal gaps. The 18-test final suite covers 8 categories including ambiguous inputs, calendar boundaries, and mixed formats that the initial tests completely missed."

⊢= obs-accumulate-mode-essential
  given §04-self-building-test-suite
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "ACCUMULATE MODE IS ESSENTIAL FOR TEST SUITES: The ⊢⊢ spawner's accumulate mode means iteration 0's edge-test-0..5 persist when iteration 1 spawns edge-test-6..10. The wildcard deps (edge-test-*→result) resolve to ALL 11 cells. Without accumulate, iteration 1 would discard the first 6 edge tests — losing coverage that was already earned. This is the right default for test accumulation. A replace-mode spawner would be appropriate for a different pattern: re-generating a complete test set from scratch each iteration."

⊢= obs-wildcard-deps-enable-fan-in
  given §04-self-building-test-suite
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "WILDCARD DEPS ARE THE FAN-IN PRIMITIVE: assess-coverage uses edge-test-*→result, edge-test-*→verdict, and given? edge-test-*→deeper-edges to collect outputs from ALL spawned test cells. Without wildcards, assess-coverage would need to enumerate edge-test-0, edge-test-1, ..., edge-test-10 — impossible since the count isn't known at authoring time. Wildcards make assess-coverage agnostic to spawn count. The v0.2 spec formalizes what R16 programs already needed: dynamic fan-in from spawned cell populations."

⊢= obs-guard-clauses-replace-score-check
  given §04-self-building-test-suite
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "GUARD CLAUSES SPLIT SUCCESS/FAILURE CLEANLY: R16 had a single final-test-suite cell that had to handle both high-coverage and low-coverage outcomes in its ∴ body. v0.2 splits this into final-report (where coverage-score >= 8) and needs-more-work (where coverage-score < 8). Only one fires. The skipped cell's yields become ⊥. This is structurally identical to the emit-success/emit-failure pattern in program 03. Guard clauses turn branching from a procedural concern (if/else in ∴) into a structural concern (graph topology)."

⊢= obs-oracle-retry-catches-logical-error
  given §04-self-building-test-suite
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "ORACLE RETRY CAUGHT A REAL LOGICAL ERROR: assess-coverage in iteration 1 initially yielded gaps=[] with coverage-score=8, violating the oracle '⊨ if len(gaps) = 0 then coverage-score >= 9'. The file-scope ⊨? triggered a retry, and the LLM corrected itself by adding the two remaining minor gaps. This is the oracle system doing exactly what it's designed for: catching inconsistencies between yields. The coverage was genuinely 8/10 (not 9), so gaps SHOULD exist. The oracle prevented an internally inconsistent output from freezing."

⊢= obs-given-optional-bootstrap
  given §04-self-building-test-suite
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "given? BREAKS TWO CIRCULAR DEPENDENCIES: (1) discover-edge-cases uses given? refine-test-suite→refined-edge-cases — on iteration 0, no refined cases exist yet, so it's ⊥ and discover works from scratch. On iteration 1+, refined cases are available and incorporated. (2) assess-coverage uses given? edge-test-*→deeper-edges — if some edge tests don't produce deeper edges, the empty list is handled gracefully. Both uses follow the ⊥-as-bootstrap pattern: accept absence on first contact, use the value when available."

⊢= obs-aspirational-oracles-feedback-loop
  given §04-self-building-test-suite
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "ASPIRATIONAL ORACLES SERVE AS QUALITY SIGNALS: discover-edge-cases has 4 oracles but is managed by ⊢∘ evolve. Under v0.2 rules, these oracles are aspirational — they describe target quality but don't independently block freezing. Their failure messages feed into the through chain (assess-coverage → refine-test-suite), which uses them to guide improvement. The actual convergence gate is 'until assess-coverage→coverage-score >= 8'. This separation is clean: oracles say what SHOULD be true, the until condition says when to STOP."
